{"id":14881377,"mediaExerciseId":"37b1f21e-c2d8-4e6f-90a6-adf42de072ae","exerciseName":"6","chapterName":"12","chapterTitle":"Some Lessons From Capital Market History","groupId":612365,"groupTitle":"Minicase Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":419,"solutions":[{"id":6253470,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we are to make a personal decision in choosing which portfolio allocation to choose. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"For a university student like me who does not have that much investing power yet due to limited financial resources, the choice would be between the S&P 500 fund or the Money Market Fund. \n\nThese are the top choices since it provides a very low risk compared to the other funds. Additionally, the fees are also manageable which means that despite the returns not being very big, you still get a huge chunk of the returns since the fees are minimal. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Another option, for people with higher buying power, they can also consider Large-Company stock fund since it has been overperforming the market for quite a lot. This is also suited for people with higher risk appetite since it is more volatile than the money market or the S&P 500 funds. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"9192391b-27f2-4d87-a223-d60cf7f7627f","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0